    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1946-02-01T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1946-02-01T00:00:00-05:00" n="4"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d4">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">710 Consultation (4)/2–146</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Memorandum of Conversation, by the Director of the Office of
                        American Republic Affairs</hi> (<hi rend="italic">Briggs</hi>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1946-02-01">February 1,
                            1946</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <table>
                    <row>
                        <cell rendition="#top #nowrap">Participants:</cell>
                        <cell rendition="#hanging">
                            <gloss target="#t_ABr1">A–Br</gloss>—Mr. Braden</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell/>
                        <cell rendition="#hanging">
                            <gloss target="#t_ARA1">ARA</gloss>—Mr. Briggs</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell/>
                        <cell rendition="#hanging">Mr. C. B. Pearson, Canadian Ambassador</cell>
                    </row>
                </table>
                <p>During a call on Mr. Braden on February 1 on other matters, the Canadian
                    Ambassador mentioned the pending Rio Treaty, indicating <pb facs="0022" n="4"
                        xml:id="pg_4"/> that the clause in the United States draft making possible
                    adherence by Canada (but not mentioning Canada by name) is entirely satisfactory
                    to his Government. He expressed his appreciation of our courtesy in making a
                    copy of the draft available for the confidential information of his
                    Government.</p>
                <p>Ambassador Pearson then inquired concerning the prospects for holding the Rio
                    Conference, and Mr. Braden outlined to him the present situation, including our
                    views relative to the Argentine situation.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>E. O. B[<hi rend="smallcaps">riggs</hi>]</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
